revision.text:
'''Annie Aggens''' is a [[List of Arctic expeditions|polar expedition]] leader for Polar Explorers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/last-frontier-beckons-for-wellheeled-thrill-seekers-1056593.html|title=Last frontier beckons for well-heeled thrill seekers - Independent.ie|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.polarexplorers.com/OurGuides.htm Annie Aggens guide bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915060317/http://www.polarexplorers.com/OurGuides.htm |date=September 15, 2008 }}</ref> She is one of only a few women who have led treks to both the [[North Pole|North]] and [[South Pole]]s.
In May 2008, she led an international team on a 25-day trek across the [[Greenland Ice Cap]].<ref>[http://www.chicagopublicradio.org/Content.aspx?audioID=23150 Chicago Public Radio Richard Steel interview with Annie Aggens]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She is also the co-author, with [[Chris Townsend (writer)|Chris Townsend]], of the ''Encyclopedia of Outdoor & Wilderness Skills: The Ultimate A-Z Guide for The Adventurous.'' 2003. Ragged Mountain Press. {{ISBN|0-07-138406-5}}.
In 2006, she founded ICECAAP,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projecticecap.com/|title=ICECAAP|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> an international [[consortium]] of polar explorers dedicated to preserving the polar environment.
