'''Mavis Lilian Batey''', [[Order of British Empire|MBE]] (née Lever; 5 May 1921 – 12 November 2013), was an English [[World War II cryptography|code-breaker during World War II]]. Her work at [[Bletchley Park]] was one of the keys to the success of [[D-Day]].<ref name=tele-obit>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/special-forces-obituaries/10447712/Mavis-Batey-obituary.html|title=Mavis Batey |date=13 November 2013|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref> She later became a [[garden historian]], who campaigned to save historic parks and gardens, and an author.<ref name="PG">{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Sarah|accessdate=2018-03-21|title=Mavis Batey: from codebreaker to campaigner for historic parks and gardens - Parks & Gardens UK|url=http://www.parksandgardens.org/further-reading/explore/175-contemporaryy-profiles/335-mavis-batey:-from-codebreaker-to-campaigner-for-historic-parks-and-gardens|website=www.parksandgardens.org|p=1}}</ref> Batey was awarded the [[Veitch Memorial Medal]] in 1985, and made a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in 1987, in both cases for her work on the conservation of gardens.<ref name=Jackson>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Sarah|accessdate=2018-03-18|title=Mavis Batey: from codebreaker to campaigner for historic parks and gardens - Parks & Gardens UK|url=http://www.parksandgardens.org/explore/topics/175-contemporary-profiles/335-mavis-batey?showall=&start=3|website=www.parksandgardens.org|p=4}}</ref>

==Early life==
Mavis Lilian Lever was born on 5 May 1921<ref name="PG"/> in [[Dulwich]] to her seamstress mother and postal worker father. She was brought up in [[Norbury]] and went to [[Coloma Convent Girls' School]] in [[Croydon]].<ref name="guardObit"/> She was studying German at [[University College, London]] at the outbreak of World War II, concentrating on the [[German romantics]]. She decided to interrupt her studies to assist with the war effort. Originally, she applied to be a nurse, but discovered that her linguistic skills were in high demand.<ref name="theheroinecollective.com">{{cite news|accessdate=2018-03-18|title=BIOGRAPHY: Mavis Batey - Code-Breaker - The Heroine Collective|url=http://www.theheroinecollective.com/mavis-batey/|newspaper=The Heroine Collective|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>

==Codebreaker==
{{See also|Women in Bletchley Park|Bletchley Park#Personnel}}
At first she was employed by the London Section to check the [[personal advertisement|personal columns]] of ''[[The Times]]'' for coded spy messages.<ref>Barwick, Sandra. ''A cracking time at Bletchley'' [[The Daily Telegraph]], 16 January 1999</ref> Then, in 1940, she was recruited to work as a codebreaker at Bletchley Park.<ref name="PG"/> She worked as an assistant to [[Dilly Knox]], and was closely involved in the decryption effort before the [[Battle of Cape Matapan|Battle of Matapan]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Friedrich Ludwig Bauer|title=Decrypted Secrets: Methods and Maxims of Cryptology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s9y9p2jP6pQC&pg=PA432|accessdate=25 July 2013|date=January 2002|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-540-42674-5|page=432}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Hugh Sebag-Montefiore|title=Enigma|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yLnEK-kBcQEC&pg=PT254|accessdate=25 July 2013|date=21 July 2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1-78022-123-6|page=254}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Alex Frame|title=Flying Boats: My Father's War in the Mediterranean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0kWcncvokjUC&pg=PA183|accessdate=25 July 2013|year=2007|publisher=Victoria University Press|isbn=978-0-86473-562-1|pages=183–4 note 91}}</ref> According to ''The Daily Telegraph'', she became so familiar with the styles of individual enemy operators that she could determine that two of them had a girlfriend called Rosa. Batey had developed a successful technique that could be used elsewhere.<ref name=tom>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/world-war-two/11151478/Could-you-have-been-a-codebreaker-at-Bletchley-Park.html|title=Could you have been a codebreaker at Bletchley Park?|author=Tom Chivers|work=Daily Telegrapg|date=12 October 2014|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>

Although Mavis was just 19, she started working on the Italian Naval Enigma machine, and by late March of 1941 she effectively broke into their framework, deciphering a message which said "Today's the day minus three". She and her colleagues worked for three days and nights and discovered that the Italians were intending to assault a Royal Navy convoy transporting supplies from Cairo, Egypt to Greece.<ref name="theheroinecollective.com"/> <ref name=tele-obit/>The messages they deciphered provided a detailed plan of the Italian assault.<ref name="tandfonline.com">{{cite journal|first1=David H.|last1=Hamer|title=Review ofFrom Bletchley with Loveby Mavis Batey|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01611190902788825|journal=Cryptologia|pages=274–275|volume=33|issue=3|doi=10.1080/01611190902788825}}</ref>

In December 1941 she broke a message between Belgrade and Berlin that enabled Knox's team to work out the wiring of the [[Cryptanalysis of the Enigma#Abwehr Enigma|Abwehr Enigma]], an [[Enigma machine]] previously thought to be unbreakable.<ref name="guardObit"/> Later, Batey broke another Abwehr machine, the GGG. This enabled the British to be able to read the Abwehr messages and confirm that the Germans believed the Double-Cross intelligence they were being fed by the double agents who were recruited by Britain as spies.<ref name=tele-obit/>

While at Bletchley Park she met [[Keith Batey]], a mathematician and fellow codebreaker whom she married in 1942.<ref name="PG"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=Francis H. Hinsley|author2=Alan Stripp|title=Codebreakers: The Inside Story of Bletchley Park|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1MC2d2LPAcC&pg=PA129|accessdate=25 July 2013|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-280132-6|page=129}}</ref>

==Publications==  

Mavis Batey wrote a biography of Dilly Knox: ‘Dilly: The Man Who Broke Enigmas’.                                            The book gives a summary of the government codes and cypher school's codebreaking operation in Bletchley Park. It also describes her code breaking of the Italian Enigma which contributed to the British Navy's success at the [[Battle of Cape Matapan]].<ref name="tandfonline.com"/>

==Later life and awards==
Batey spent some time after 1945 in the Diplomatic Service, and then brought up three children, two daughters and a son.<ref name="Fawcett">Edward Fawcett, ''The Genius of the Scene'', Garden History Vol. 24, No. 1 (Summer, 1996), pp. 1–2. Published by: The Garden History Society. Stable URL: https://www.jstor.org/stable/1587088</ref> She published a number of books on garden history, as well as some relating to Bletchley Park, and served as President of the [[Garden History Society]], of which she became Secretary in 1971.<ref name="Fawcett"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Mavis Batey|title=Essays in Honour of Mavis Batey: President of the Garden History Society, Presented in Celebration of Her 75th Birthday|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I55EOwAACAAJ|accessdate=25 July 2013|year=1996|publisher=Maney}}</ref>

She was awarded the [[Veitch Memorial Medal]] in 1985, and made a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in 1987, in both cases for her work on the conservation of gardens.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-03-18|title=Mrs Mavis Lilian Batey - Summary|url=http://www.parksandgardens.org/places-and-people/person/1921|website=www.parksandgardens.org}}</ref><ref name= Jackson/>

Batey, aged 92 and a widow since 2010, died on 12 November 2013.<ref name=tele-obit/><ref name="guardObit">{{cite web|url=http://www.societyofauthors.org/cholmondeley-past-winners|title=Mavis Batey |last1=Smith|first1=Michael|date=20 November 2013 |website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=27 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Douglas | last=Martin | title=Mavis Batey, Allied Code Breaker in World War II, Dies at 92 
| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/23/world/europe/mavis-batey-world-war-ii-code-breaker-dies-at-92.html?hp&_r=0 |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 22, 2013 }}</ref>

