{{About|Melia, mother of Amycus|other mythological characters named Melia|Melia (mythology)}}
In [[Greek mythology]], '''Melia''' or '''Melie''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: Μελίη) was a [[Bithynia]]n [[nymph]], who was, by [[Poseidon]], the mother of [[Amycus]] and [[Mygdon of Bebryces|Mygdon]], both kings of the [[Bebryces]].<ref>Parada, s.v. Melie p. 115; Hard, p. 386; Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D20%3Aentry%3Damycus-bio-1 s.v. Amycus], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DM%3Aentry+group%3D32%3Aentry%3Dmygdon-bio-1 s.v. Mygdon]; [[Hyginus]], ''[[Fabulae]]'' 17; [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], ''[[Argonautica]]'' [https://archive.org/stream/argonautica00apoluoft#page/102/mode/2up 2.1&ndash;4]; [[Maurus Servius Honoratus|Servius]], ''Commentary on the Aeneid of Vergil'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0053%3Abook%3D5%3Acommline%3D373 5.373]; described only as "a Bithynian nymph" at [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], [http://data.perseus.org/citations/urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0548.tlg001.perseus-eng1:1.9.20 1.9.20] (see Frazer's note).</ref> The name Melia perhaps derived from a misreading of a line of [[Apollonius of Rhodes]] containing ''Βιθυνὶς Μελίη'', which instead of being read as Melia from Bithynia, might instead be read as Bithynis the [[Meliae|Melia]], i.e. Bithynis the ash tree nymph.<ref>Cameron, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fnJ2CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT321&dq=%22Bithynian+nymph%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjj6aSaw9DPAhVCfiYKHfahAKoQ6AEIUDAI#v=onepage&q=%22Bithynian%20nymph%22&f=false p. 264].</ref>
