[[File:Franciszek Siedlecki - Rusałki.jpg|thumb|Rusalkas, a type of minor goddesses, represented by Franciszek Siedlecki.]]
In [[Slavic paganism]] there are a variety of female [[tutelary deity|tutelary spirits]] associated with water. They have been compared to the Greek ''[[Nymph]]s'',{{sfn|Máchal|1918|pp=253–255}} and they may be either white (beneficent) or black (maleficent).{{sfn|Máchal|1918|p=259}} They may be called '''Boginka''' (plural ''Boginky'') literally "little goddess",{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}} '''Navia''' (and '''Navka''' or '''Mavka''', pl. ''Navy'', ''Navky''),{{sfn|Máchal|1918|pp=253–255}} '''Rusalka''' (pl. ''Rusalky''),{{sfn|Mathieu-Colas|2017}} and '''Vila''' (plural ''Vily'').{{sfn|Máchal|1918|pp=256–259}}

The [[Proto-Slavic]] root *''navь-'', which forms one of the names for these beings, means "dead",{{sfn|Kempiński|2001}} as these minor goddesses are conceived as the spirits of dead children or young women. They are represented as half-naked beautiful girls with long hair, but in the South Slavic tradition also as birds who soar in the depths of the skies. They live in waters, woods and steppes, and they giggle, sing, play music and clap their hands. They are so beautiful that they bewitch young men and might bring them to death by drawing them into deep water.{{sfn|Máchal|1918|pp=253–255}}

==Etymology==
''Navia'', spelled in various ways in the [[Slavic languages]], refers to the souls of the dead.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}} ''Navka'' and ''Mavka'' (pl. ''Navky'' and ''Mavky'') are variations with the diminutive suffix -''ka''. They are also known as ''Lalka'' (pl. ''Lalky'').{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004|pp=79, 199, 206}} The Proto-Slavic root *''navь-'', means "dead", "deceased" or "corpse".{{sfn|Kempiński|2001}} The word [[Prav-Yav-Nav|''Nav'']] is also the name of the [[underworld]], [[Vyraj]], which is presided by the chthonic god [[Veles (god)|Veles]].{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}}

The world of the dead is believed to be separated from the world of the living either by a sea or a river located deep underground.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}} In the folk beliefs of [[Ruthenia]], Veles lives in a swamp located at the centre of Nav, sitting on a golden throne at the base of the [[axis mundi|world tree]], and wielding a sword.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}} Symbolically, the Nav is also described as a huge green plain–pasture, onto which Veles guides the souls.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}} The entrance to Nav is guarded by a ''[[Slavic dragon|zmey]]'', a dragon.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}}

According to [[Stanisław Urbańczyk]], amongst other scholars, ''Navia'' was a general name for demons arising from the souls of tragic and premature deaths, the killers and the killed, warlocks, and the drowned.{{sfn|Strzelczyk|2007}} They were said to be hostile and unfavourable towards the living, being jealous of life.{{sfn|Strzelczyk|2007}} In [[Bulgaria]]n folklore there exists the character of twelve Navias who suck the blood out of women giving birth, whereas in the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' the Navias are presented as a demonic personification of the 1092 plague in [[Polotsk]].{{sfn|Kempiński|2001}} According to folk beliefs, Navias may take the form of birds.{{sfn|Szyjewski|2004}}

==Types of minor goddesses==
[[File:Rusalka and her daughter.jpg|thumb|A Rusalka and her daughter, by I. Volkov, 1899.]]

===Rusalka===
{{main|Rusalka}}
According to [[Vladimir Propp]], ''Rusalka'' (pl. ''Rusalky'') was an appellation used by the early Slavs for tutelary deities of water who favour fertility, and they were not considered evil entities before the nineteenth century. They came out of the water in spring to transfer life-giving moisture to the fields, thus nurturing the crops.{{sfnm|1a1=Ivanits|1y=1989|1pp=78–81|2a1=Wayland Barber|2y=2013|2p=18}}

In nineteenth-century descriptions, however, the Rusalka became an unquiet, dangerous, [[unclean spirit]] (''[[Nav (Slavic folklore)|Nav]]''). According to [[Dmitry Zelenin (ethnographer)|Dmitry Zelenin]],{{sfn|Ivanits|1989|p=76}} young women, who either committed suicide by drowning due to an unhappy marriage (they might have been jilted by their lovers or abused and harassed by their much older husbands) or who were violently drowned against their will (especially after becoming pregnant with unwanted children), must live out their designated time on earth as Rusalkas. Original Slavic lore suggests that not all Rusalkas were linked with death from water.{{sfn|Wayland Barber|2013|p=18}}

They appear in the form of beautiful girls, with long hair, generally naked but covered with their long tresses, with wreaths of sedge on their heads. They live in groups in crystal palaces at the bottom of rivers, emerging only in springtime; others live in fields and forests. In springtime, they dance and sing along the riverbanks promoting the growth of rye. After the first thunder, they return to their rivers or rise to the skies.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Rusalka|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?linkpath=pages\R\U\RusalkaIT.htm|encyclopedia=Internet [[Encyclopedia of Ukraine]]|publisher=Canadian Institute of Ukrainian Studies, [[University of Toronto Press]]|date=2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207094031/http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?linkpath=pages%5CR%5CU%5CRusalkaIT.htm|archive-date=7 February 2018|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>

They were worshipped together with ancestors during the ''[[Rosalia (festival)|Rosalia]]'' (or ''Rusalye'') festival in spring, originally a Roman festival for offering [[rose]]s (and other flowers) to gods and ancestors; from the festival derives the term ''Rusalka'' itself.{{sfn|Machál|1916|pp=254, 311–312}} Another time associated with the Rusalkas is the [[green week]] (or ''Rusalnaya nedelja'', "week of the Rusalkas") in early June; a common feature of this celebration was the ritual banishment or burial of the Rusalka at the end of the week, which remained popular in Russia, Belarus, and Ukraine until the 1930s.{{sfn|Ivanits|1989|p=80}}

They were worshipped together with ancestors during the ''[[Rosalia (festival)|Rosalia]]'' (or ''Rusallia'') festival in spring, originally a Roman festival for offering [[rose]]s (and other flowers) to gods and ancestors whose practice spread among the South Slavs and from them to other Slavs; from the festival derives the term ''Rusalka'' itself.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Mushynka|first=Mykola|title=Rosalia|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?linkpath=pages%5CR%5CO%5CRosalia.htm|encyclopedia=Internet [[Encyclopedia of Ukraine]]|publisher=Canadian Institute of Ukrainian Studies, [[University of Toronto Press]]|date=2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207064322/http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?linkpath=pages%5CR%5CO%5CRosalia.htm|archive-date=7 February 2018}}</ref>

===Vila===
[[File:Artgate Fondazione Cariplo - Giuliano Bartolomeo, Le Villi.jpg|thumb|Vilas (''Le Villi'', 1906) as represented by [[Bartolomeo Giuliano]].]]
''Vila'' (pl. ''Vily'') are another type of minor goddesses, already identified as Nymphs by the Greek historian [[Procopius]]; their name comes from the same root as the name of Veles. They are described as beautiful, eternally young, dressed in white, with eyes flashing like thunders, and provided with wings. They live in the clouds, in mountain woods or in the waters. They are well-disposed towards men, and they are able to turn themselves into horses, wolves, snakes, falcons and swans. The cult of the Vilas was still practised among South Slavs in the early twentieth century, with offerings of fruits and flowers in caves, cakes near wells, and ribbons hanged to the branches of trees.{{sfn|Máchal|1918|pp=256–259}}

